The benches do not reflect high-quality standards as requested under clause 3.2 (b) of the contract. The benches have not been delivered at the exact place. In this regard, the photos uploaded by the counterparty does not have any quantitative data suitable to check geolocalization, as it should be according to clause 3.3(e) of the contract. The photos only visually indicate that the delivery happened at a Radboud location, but it was not the exact one (see the photo uploaded in the resolution proof shared folder).
In light of the above, I am asking for a major reduction of the price to compensate the extra transport costs and the damage suffered as a result of the lower quality of the benches.

According to clause 3.2 (c) I communicated, at the beginning of the 6th month, in written form that an improvement in terms of content was requested, as we did not reach 5 interactions per day (on the Facebook channel) as in accordance to clause 3.2 (a) iv, during the 5th month of the contract. 
In the light of the above, I am asking for a fair reduction of the price, as now we do not have time left in the contract to adjust the trend.

John's proposal seems fairest to me because John has lived up to the contract to the best of his abilities with the information and feedback provided to him. The inconvenice that Radboud has encountered can't possibly warrant the level of compensation as requested by Radboud and as such I think that John should be paid as per his proposal where he is already compensating for the errors made in the lack of communication.

As another voter mentioned the contract does not contain a provision with regards to the quality of the service. However such a provision is very uncommon in this field of work. Search  for templates on the internet for social media freelancer contracts and you will find no such a provision. In addition it is self explanatory that the service provided should be of a professional level and of atleast a level higher than Borrel could have done themselves. This is why my vote goes to Borrel.

I think neither party is right in its argumentation. However, Resolution proof and the contract require Carpenter to upload a certain number of photos, which I do not see. Therefore, I consider Carpenter failed in his obligation and I vote for Radboud as the closest to what I consider fair.

Christopher Leaner did not comply with clause 5.2 (d). He should have informed us that the trash containers were going to be full such that we could have prevented it, on the contrary, he deposited the extra trash out of the containers without notifying. This behavior amounts to an infringement of the contract and at the same time, it provoked the municipality to sanction us. 
Geolocation indications are missing.
In light of the above, the overall quality is lower than the price paid, so we ask for a price reduction. The reduction also takes into account the economic value of the fine.

Borrel did not complete his contractual obligation to provide Mr. Tortellini with the needed feedback regarding the quality of work. Next to that the 5 interactions are in reference to interactions which should have been executed by Tortellini, which does not seem to be the problem Borrel is referring to. Mr. Tortellini is just bound to deliver the content which he did even after the requested fix, he and the contract provide no quotum of interactions which have to be executed by the public. The fault lies with Borrel here as they have not given Mr. Tortellini the required feedback

Leaner was simply negligent in following the terms of the contract. 
He ought to have provided geolocational data, for which there are many means, even without a phone number, such as providing a trackable google maps link via email. 

Next to that, the laziness failure to inform the Lab, as demonstrated by Leaner constitute an unquestionable breach of contract for which the Lab should be compensated

The freelancer was expected to create a unique illustration for each page, so as to reflect the course of the story, instead for 5 pages he reused the same illustration. I therefore ask for a reduction of the fee of 100 JUR  for each page not illustrated in accordance with the Contract. In addition, I ask for a refund of an additional 50 JUR per reused image for the loss of time and damage resulting from this, since the product was expected to be launched on the market after the completion of the works governed by the Contract. The overall amount to pay is 500+250 = 750 JUR.

It seems unfair that Lab for New Justice did not accept the fact that the issue is caused by its own peak in garbage production, and it seems to me that Leaner acted respecting the contract which stated clearly to clean in the inside. Moreover, there is no trace such fine in terms of a receipt or a bill.

The freelancer was expecte to create a horse resemplbing the one appearing in the picture (uploaded in the shared folder). Although the drafts were satisfying and the final draft was approved, the final product as it apppears on the book looks quite different. It surely does not resemble the one in the picture. We believe it is very distorted from the one in the last approved draft. We find its eyes grotesque, which can be scary to children, and we do not like the spots on the belly, which are barely visible but are central to the story told in the book. Because of shortage of time we cannot find another drawer or do the job again, but we find it fair to pay half of the accorded money to Anna Schmidt.
